\begin_layout Subsubsection
\noindent
Integrierender Faktor
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Integrierender Faktor 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(x,y\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Die DGL
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(x,y\right)dx+q\left(x,y\right)dy=0$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

 ist im allgemeinen nicht exakt.
 Um sie in eine exakte DGL umzuformen, müssen wir sie mit einer stetig differenz
ierbaren Funktion 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(x,y\right)$
\end_inset

, dem sogenannten integrierenden Faktor oder auch Eulerschen Multiplikator,
 multiplizieren:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(x,y\right)p\left(x,y\right)dx+\mu\left(x,y\right)q\left(x,y\right)dy=0$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Diese DGL ist genau dann exakt, wenn die Integrabilitätsbedingung erfüllt
 ist:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \frac{\partial\left(\mu p\right)}{\partial y}=\frac{\partial\left(\mu q\right)}{\partial x}}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Diese partielle Differentialgleichung ist in der Regel aufwändiger zu lösen
 als die ursprüngliche gewöhnliche DGL.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Nimmt man 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 als Funktion einer Variable 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 an, welche ihrerseits eine Funktion von 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 und 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 ist, dann erhält man:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \mu=\mu\left(u\left(x,y\right)\right)}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \frac{d\mu}{du}\frac{\partial u}{\partial y}p+\mu\frac{\partial p}{\partial y}=\frac{d\mu}{du}\frac{\partial u}{\partial x}q+\mu\frac{\partial q}{\partial x}}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \mu'\left(u_{y}p-u_{x}q\right)=\mu\left(q_{x}-p_{y}\right)}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Box Boxed
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width "27.4col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \frac{\mu'}{\mu}=\frac{q_{x}-p_{y}}{u_{y}p-u_{x}q}=f\left(u\right)}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Nun muss man 
\begin_inset Formula $u\left(x,y\right)$
\end_inset

 so bestimmen, dass die rechte Seite der Gleichung eine Funktion von 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 ist.
 Die Gleichung lässt sich dann integrieren:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \ln\left|\mu\left(u\right)\right|=\int f\left(u\right)du}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \mu\left(u\right)=e^{\int f\left(u\right)du}}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Einsetzen von 
\begin_inset Formula $u\left(x,y\right)$
\end_inset

 liefert den integrierenden Faktor 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(x,y\right)$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Häufige Funktionen für 
\begin_inset Formula $u\left(x,y\right)$
\end_inset

 sind:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\noindent
\begin_inset Formula $u\left(x,y\right)=x$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \frac{p_{y}-q_{x}}{q}=f\left(x\right)}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\noindent
\begin_inset Formula $u\left(x,y\right)=y$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \frac{q_{x}-p_{y}}{p}=f\left(y\right)}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\noindent
\begin_inset Formula $u\left(x,y\right)=x+y$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \frac{q_{x}-p_{y}}{p-q}=f\left(x+y\right)}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\noindent
\begin_inset Formula $u\left(x,y\right)=x^{2}+y^{2}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \frac{q_{x}-p_{y}}{2yp-2xq}=f\left(x^{2}+y^{2}\right)}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\noindent
\begin_inset Formula $u\left(x,y\right)=xy$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \frac{q_{x}-p_{y}}{xp-yq}=f\left(xy\right)}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\noindent
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle u\left(x,y\right)=\frac{y}{x}}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \frac{q_{x}-p_{y}}{\frac{1}{x}p+\frac{y}{x^{2}}q}=x^{2}\frac{q_{x}-p_{y}}{xp+yq}=f\left(\frac{y}{x}\right)}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Die Lösung der modifizierten exakten DGL ist gleich der Lösung der ursprüngliche
n DGL.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Beispiel:
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx}=\frac{\tan\left(y\right)}{x}=\frac{1}{x\cot\left(y\right)}}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle dx-x\cot\left(y\right)dy=0}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(x,y\right)=1$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $q\left(x,y\right)=-x\cot\left(y\right)$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \frac{\partial p}{\partial y}=0\neq-\cot\left(y\right)=\frac{\partial q}{\partial x}}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Die ursprüngliche Gleichung ist also nicht exakt.
 Wir wählen für den integrierenden Faktor
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \mu=\mu\left(y\right)}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \frac{-\cot\left(y\right)}{1}=-\cot\left(y\right)=f\left(y\right)}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \int f\left(y\right)dy=-\int\frac{\cos\left(y\right)}{\sin\left(y\right)}dy=-\ln\left|\sin\left(y\right)\right|}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \mu\left(y\right)=e^{-\ln\left|\sin\left(y\right)\right|}=\frac{1}{\sin\left(y\right)}}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Beim letzten Gleichheitszeichen haben wir 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\sin\left(y\right)\right|$
\end_inset

 durch 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin\left(y\right)$
\end_inset

 ersetzt.
 Die Funktion 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 soll ja stetig differenzierbar sein.
 Wir erhalten die modifizierte DGL:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \frac{dx}{\sin\left(y\right)}-x\frac{\cot\left(y\right)}{\sin\left(y\right)}dy=\frac{dx}{\sin\left(y\right)}-x\frac{\cos\left(y\right)}{\sin^{2}\left(y\right)}dy=0}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \tilde{p}\left(x,y\right)=\frac{1}{\sin\left(y\right)}}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \tilde{q}\left(x,y\right)=-x\frac{\cos\left(y\right)}{\sin^{2}\left(y\right)}}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Diese DGL ist nun exakt, da:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \frac{\partial\tilde{p}}{\partial y}=-\frac{\cos\left(y\right)}{\sin^{2}\left(y\right)}=\frac{\partial\tilde{q}}{\partial x}}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Als Potentialfunktion erhalten wir:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle F\left(x,y\right)=\int\frac{1}{\sin\left(y\right)}dx+\int\left(-x\frac{\cos\left(y\right)}{\sin^{2}\left(y\right)}-\frac{\partial}{\partial y}\int\frac{1}{\sin\left(y\right)}dx\right)dy}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \hphantom{F\left(x,y\right)}=\frac{x}{\sin\left(y\right)}+\int\left(-x\frac{\cos\left(y\right)}{\sin^{2}\left(y\right)}-\frac{\partial}{\partial y}\frac{x}{\sin\left(y\right)}\right)dy}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \hphantom{F\left(x,y\right)}=\frac{x}{\sin\left(y\right)}+\int\left(-x\frac{\cos\left(y\right)}{\sin^{2}\left(y\right)}+x\frac{\cos\left(x\right)}{\sin^{2}\left(y\right)}\right)dy=\frac{x}{\sin\left(y\right)}+\int0dy}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle F\left(x,y\right)=\frac{x}{\sin\left(y\right)}=C}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Die Lösung der ursprünglichen Differentialgleichung lautet also:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle y\left(x\right)=\arcsin\left(cx\right)}$
\end_inset

 mit 
\begin_inset Formula $c:=C^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\square$
\end_inset


